Students shine at Zhejiang University annual academic conference
Air is used to wash hands, breath is used to judge diseases, and precise search for the source of haze. Last night, a series of creative academic achievements were commended at the opening ceremony of Zhejiang University Academic Annual Conference in 2016.
The principal investigators on these results are students, and the research covers a wide range of areas including environment, mechanical, energy, medical, life sciences, and humanities. Students have created many high-end inventions with application value from a curious idea, and some of these projects have won awards at home and abroad.
BioSensors: Your family's health checkup doctor
The team led by Dr. Di-Ming Zhang, a biomedical engineering Ph.D. candidate, demonstrated a biosensor for smartphones that is half the size of a typical smartphone.
After exhaling, a health report will be displayed on the smartphone, according to Zhang.
The smart bracelets that can detect health conditions on the market generally detect physical parameters such as temperature and pulse.
This new biosensor uses graphene, a new material that targets chemical elements. Its keen “sense of smell” allows it to reflect the body’s condition in greater depth and accuracy.
Intelligent surgical lights: doctor's super eyes
In addition to smartphones, smart operating lights are now used in operating rooms.
The invention won a silver medal at this years 44th Geneva Invention Convention.
The research team led by doctoral students Linjing Zhu and Junfei Shen has developed a new type of shadowless LED surgical lamp, aiming to overcome the defects of traditional surgical lamps.
For example, if doctors cannot see all the tumor tissue during an early cancer checkup, the cancer cells will spread later, he said.
This smart surgical light has four panels that can be tuned to enhance the contrast of different tissues.
During the procedure, the doctor can adjust the spot size, brightness, spectrum, color homogeneity, and shadow-free rate to meet the needs of the surgery and individual preferences.
This intelligent surgical light has been used in hospitals such as Sir Run Run Shaw Hospital and Children's Hospital of Zhejiang University School of Medicine, which has received positive feedback.
Last October, the invention won first prize in the National Challenge Cup.
Washing hands with air
While ordinary people wash their hands by running water, using soap or hand sanitizer, Li Qizhang and his classmates invented an air-handwashing device.
Standing on the washbasin of a device, our weight squeezes the air out.
Color development and bacterial residue tests showed that this technique was as effective as the regular handwashing method.
The device uses only our own weight as driving force, which can ensure the degree of cleaning and save 90% water. It's energy-saving and environment-friendly.
Last year, it won the only gold award at the 2nd Global Major Challenges Summit, standing out among hundreds of inventions from the world’s best universities.
