To conclude, I personally believe that "All Along the River" is a total fiasco, in every sense of that phrase.
But to say there's nothing of note about it at all, that would be a lie. At least the soundtrack is good.
Bad movies come in many types, from the kind that put you to sleep to the kind that leave you seething with rage. Once a Thief falls into the latter category -- and it can ignite your fury in countless ways.
Han Han has a real gift for insulting the audience.
The most painful thing about this film is that it seems to be a product of a kierkegaardian novel, indescribable and porous like the overcoat on Pao Pao.
You'll wonder if there's some kind of hidden directorial metaphor at work here, but upon further reflection you'll realize it's just a turd.
First, a little about the scenes I find hard to understand.
Her grandma's wish is to see snow, so the plot arranges for a neighbor to drive her to the snowy northeast.
Old man travels from south to northeast by van to see snow?
The old man was never heard of again.
Opening a hotel on a abandoned ship, how did the heroine's brother get the business license?
Why is it so easy for a gangster in an island drag bike to block a mountain road??
Then the truck that delivered steel bars stopped by the middle of the road, and no truck driver was found anywhere.
This prop is too obvious.
How did a bad credit, suspected thug become a police officer?
In the movie, why don't they call the police when facing usurer?
An adult who can use a smartphone but doesn't know how to open a hotel room with an access card, and so sleeps outside the door of a room he couldn't find the owner of?
These inexplicable things were all over the film, so outrageous that they actually hurt when I try to remember them.
Besides the plot, what's worse is the film's theme, or lack thereof, which is a hideous, stitched monster.
The opening scenes would have you think this is a comedy, twenty minutes in you'd think it might be a inspirational film, halfway through you'd think it's trying to tell the struggles of living in a small town, and at the end you're just left wondering what exactly you watched and questioning yourself deeply why you went to a cinema to watch a film about...excrement.
For most people it's a matter of recognizing the genre tropes, like you want to shoot a biker movie, so it's going to be an inspirational comedy with a story of a talented neophyte who gets a chance to succeed.
If you want to make a love movie, then just tell the story of a town kid who likes motorbikes and a waitress girl.
If you're going to reflect reality, at least don't have things in your plot that contradict the normal world.
(like the one that just got burned and still can sing in Yoon's new movie), so don't open any crazy ideas you can't even stand for Kennedy.
The actress is not mentally challenged but in some scenes she acts like a 5 year old. I don't know if that's director's request or her acting skill.
One thing I also don't understand,why is Han so keen on adding car crash scenes in his movies?
Is this kind of movie arranged in the Spring Festival to give audience a bad mood?
