Extra virgin olive oil is the oil obtained by mechanical cold pressing of fresh olives and filtered to remove foreign matter.
According to acidity can be divided into three levels:
Extra virgin olive oil is the highest grade, most quality olive oil. It is a pure natural product.
Flavor is excellent, with delicate plant fragrance and acidity no more than 1%.
Fine virgin: has a higher acidity, not exceeding 2%, and is pure and fragrant.
Refined olive oil is obtained by refining virgin olive oil with acidity levels exceeding 3.3 percent, or as it is called "extra virgin oil".
Extra virgin olive oil can be divided into two grades:
It is a blend of refined olive oil with a certain amount of extra virgin olive oil to adjust the taste and color. It has an acidity of less than 1.5% and is clear with a pale golden color.
It is extracted by solubilization from the oil residue and refined.
As you should have noticed by looking at the classification, the acidity of olive oil is a very important indicator.
You see, olives are like the grapes used to make wine. Olives from different regions and varieties produce olive oil of different quality.
Best places to grow olives:
The Mediterranean coast has the most favorable soil, climate conditions for the growth of the olive, sunshine, humidity of the air and rainfall.
Outside the Mediterranean it is grown only in suitable areas.
Oil olive picking months:
From March to June olives are blooming and setting fruit. From July to October the fruit develops and matures, changing from green to red, purple and finally black.
Picking season for the fruit is from Nov to Feb (freshness of the oil is important).
Olive oil nutrients:
Olive oil is rich in monounsaturated fatty acids, namely oleic acid, linoleic acid and linolenic acid, as well as vitamins A, B, D, E, K and antioxidants.
Olive oil is considered the best nourishing oil discovered yet.
