A girl in Hangzhou Wulin Square stood in front of a big wooden board which read "human target, ten yuan per arrow".
A photo of a girl in Hangzhou acting as a ‘target’ for a charity event went viral on the social networking sites yesterday morning.
A girl in Hangzhou’s Wulin Square stands in front of a wooden board that is slightly taller than her. The board says “human target, ten yuan per arrow”. It means that people can shoot the arrows after paying.
The incident has drawn heated discussion.
A girl who jumped into the Qiantang River in Hangzhou to protest her sister's fundraising behavior has left the local police station, a spokesman said yesterday.
In the photo, a girl with long hair is standing in front of a wooden board with the words "human target, ten yuan per arrow" written on it. Another wooden board in front of her shows her bank account number and WeChat and Alipay account numbers.
The photo caused controversy online.
Some netizens think that the move is "eye-catching begging behavior", while others sympathize with her.
Two girls, both in their early 20s and dressed attractively, were selling food at the time of the incident, a police officer told the local newspaper.
One of the girls was crying and begging people to play the game, while another girl was shouting that her friend's sister had leukemia and needed surgery.
Last night, the publicity officer of Hangzhou Public Security Bureau Xiacheng Branch told the Beijing News reporter that the girl's name was Jiali Ji and she was raising money for her elder sister Jiayan Ji.
But since the treatment still requires more than 300,000 yuan, he has no other way but to do so.
He said that two girls were used as targets and one served food but he did not participate in the process. No one was shooting arrows, just people watching and taking photos and posting them on Weibo.
The archery was not found to be controlled by police, said the public security department.
The person in charge said, "I don't advocate adopting this kind of eye-catching fundraising method."
She had left the police station after being admonished.
