In September 2020, Mr. Lu learned about a factory located in Zhangting Town, Yuyao City, Zhejiang Province through a real estate agency. After visiting the property several times, he decided to purchase it.
However, the two parties failed to reach an agreement on key contract terms such as the scope of the factory building sale and payment methods.
Mr. Lu is angry because the house he has chosen, for which he has paid a deposit and prepared the payment, the seller suddenly refused to sell it.
The court held that the failure to conclude a formal contract should not be attributed solely to the defendant, and it was reasonably presumed that the negotiation failed. Therefore, the case did not apply the deposit penalty rule, and the defendant did not need to bear the liability for breach of contract to return the deposit in double.
Recently, the court of second instance upheld the original judgment.
Use due diligence during your transactions.
When signing a contract to buy a house, you should exercise due diligence by verifying the property owner’s information, whether the house is occupied and other relevant information. You should also include specific details about the time and place of delivery in the contract to avoid disputes.
