Don't scare people at the starting line
At book fairs, self-help books are always selling well.
Many of today's self-help books preach the "best principle" --that is, first assume or imply that you can do something, and then tell you what you need to do.
It is like skipping the most important and fundamental link of how to do it.
Because of this, they all share a characteristic: either do it to the best of your ability or don't do it at all; it's 100 or 0; you're either climbing Mount Tai or sitting in one spot.
This principle of "best" is recognized by everyone as "completely correct", but 99% people will be scared off at the starting line.
Because the theory prescribes a dramatic change of direction -- "you need to make up your mind and turn over a new leaf," just where many people are weakest.
It is surely a fool's errand to shout "YOU MUST CHANGE" in the ear of a person who is set in his ways, who hates change.
Most people are either too intimidated, hesitant and indecisive to make a “change”; or they make a sudden, impulsive decision to change and take a first, brave step, but often lack persistence and endurance.
Mr. Ma's famous "From Tomorrow" is a classic example of this "universal human nature".
The biggest problem with the Best Principle is that the threshold is too high, often beyond the ordinary ability limit, leaving most people out.
Perhaps the principle of "good enough" is a way that may lead more ordinary people to relative success.
The core of the Good Enough Principle is lowering the bar. It encourages a theory of winning big with small victories - if you can't win 100, win 1 - 1 is always greater than 0, and if you can't climb Mount Tai, climb the sand dune in front of your house, because that's better than staying put.
In any case, doing something is far better than doing nothing.
The lowered threshold increases the possibility of persistence by ordinary people, and persistence in anything increases the probability of success.
The road to success is just a little longer, that's all.
In short, the best principle, though ostensibly for everybody’s success, ultimately inspires a minority; the next best principle effectively inspires a multitude, for the benefit of as many as possible.
