Metaphysics is the study of questions that cannot be answered by direct perception through rational inquiry and logic.
Metaphysics is the branch of philosophy that seeks to explain the nature of existence and the fundamental properties of the world.
The Chinese translation of "metaphysics" comes from the "Book of Changes • Commentary on the Upper Chain", which is translated by Inoue Tetsujiro (Meiji era) from the English word "metaphysic".
Metaphysical branches include ontology, natural theology, and its spin-off issues.
Ontology is the branch of philosophy which deals with the nature of existence and reality.
Naturalism which denies the existence of God.
Method naturalism is a research method that says nothing about God.
Metaphysics is the branch of philosophy that deals with the nature of consciousness and its relation to matter, especially the brain.
Dualism and monism are the two principal schools of thought on the relation between mind and body.
Epistemology is the branch of philosophy that deals with the nature, origin, and scope of knowledge.
Part I: Humanistic ethical thought, represented by Vala and Montaigne.
Part II: The ethical thought of the Reformation, represented by Calvin.
Logic is the science of the principles and standards of valid inference and proof.
Logic usually includes three parts: inductive reasoning, abductive reasoning and deductive reasoning, which can be divided into formal logic and non-formal logic.
Aesthetics is the discipline that is devoted to the study of the nature and significance of beauty.
