A programming newbie who wants to share his personal experience.
If you are thinking about entering this industry, then you could go to a training place, but if you are not sure about it, I would suggest that you study on your own, because training costs money and you will still need 6 months of your life for that.
But if you're planning to enter the industry, training is a great option, especially for those who have very little self control.
If you have strong self control, you can also choose to study by yourself, but it will be tiring.
Of course choosing a good training school is very important.
The first thing to look at is the teaching staff of this institution. If the teaching staff is not strong enough, this training institution will have no meaning. Of course, some newly opened training institutions do not have strong teaching staff.
Secondly, before choosing a training institution, it is better to inquire about the students who graduated from this institution. After all, only the students of the institution know whether the courses are good or not.
Hello, actually I don't know how to answer your question since you didn't introduce yourself. Learning is closely related to one's own situation.
Your major, age, language you want to learn and even the city you live in can all be related to the industry you want to engage in.
If you are a student and not graduated yet, or a computer professional who already graduated, I personally suggest self study if you have enough time. This is the most efficient and cost effective way. There are many offline and online training institutions now, but they have high learning cost and require you to invest more time, basically need to train intensively for 3-6 months.
But if it's what I said above, self-study is very convenient. There are many free learning resources on the Internet now, or you can go to bilibili.com to find training resources. If you don't know how to find resources, you can also contact me through the introduction to get free resources or detailed consultation.
There are also some classic books to study with the videos.
If you are not a computer science major but still willing to pay the money and time cost, I recommend going to a training class. It is not too hard to study, teachers explain in detail, there are people who can help you with questions, and you will have a learning plan and supervisor.
And now many training institutions will sign employment agreements, with the right to recommend students to companies after their study. This can save a lot of trouble in the job hunting process.
That's my opinion. I don't know your situation, so I only give you a general idea. If you have any other questions, feel free to contact me at any time.
