In the past two years, the US blockade and siege of Huawei's chips have not only put Huawei in an unprecedented predicament, but also caused huge losses to "American" companies.
The shortage of semiconductors has affected many industries around the world, such as car companies suspending production and mobile phone prices rising. Almost all industries that use chips have been deeply affected.
More and more tech titans are going the "de-beautification" route in a bid to keep their chips homegrown.
I'm sure of that because Intel is a well-established American tech giant, which has been deeply involved in the semiconductor field for decades and has a large number of talents and technical reserves. It will surely be able to rise rapidly in the short term and defeat TSMC.
However, TSMC founder Morris Chang has dismissed Intel's decision.
He was dismissive of Intel's foray into wafer fabrication because he still holds a grudge over an incident involving TSMC and Intel that occurred more than 30 years ago.
In the 1960s and 1970s, Intel was the crown jewel of American manufacturing. It was at the top of the world in semiconductors.
Until the 1980s the world’s semiconductor high-end chips were held by a handful of powerhouses.
The semiconductor industry was characterized by IDMs, where a single factory did everything from designing to manufacturing to testing a chip. Intel was the epitome of that era.
However, this model is prohibitive to many smaller semiconductor startups that face enormous upfront costs.
Soon after, Morris Chang's vision became a reality and TSMC was born.
TSMC has focused its business on the single step of wafer processing. It does not do any design work, but only provides manufacturing services.
Then, TSMC was a mere peon in front of Intel.
Morris Chang believes that Intel looked down on wafer fabrication services.
Didn't expect the guy who once looked down on the wafer fabrication giant to start his own foundry.
So, Morris says it was ironic for Intel to enter the wafer foundry business.
TSMC's market value now exceeds that of Intel.
Now TSMC is already sprinting toward 3nm while Intel still lags behind with 14nm that was introduced seven years ago.
It was not easy to keep up with him.
I won't wait.
