Gemini meteor shower photographed by Beijing astronomy lover AnJiu on December 13, 2018 in Qinghai.
It is also the second known meteor shower not spawned by a comet.
Li Peng Xiu, a council member of Tianjin Astronomical Society and an expert in popularizing astronomy, said that like a New Year blockbuster, the Geminid meteor shower occurs at the end of the year, from December 4 to 17.
The Geminid meteor shower is characterized by slow-moving meteors of various colors. It is suitable for both visual observation and astro-photography.
The Gemini meteor shower was photographed in Tianjin on December 13, 2020 by Jing Yang.
The Geminid meteor shower will peak this year at about 15:00 on December 14. The ZHR will be 150.
Gemini meteor shower recommended index chart.
The moon will be up early in the morning. It's a waxing gibbous moon on the 14th (the 11th day of the 11th lunar month). The moon will interfere with observing since it is bright. Fortunately, the moon will set in the second half of the night and Gemini will be higher then.
Friends who like meteor shower can observe in the last few hours after the moon sets in the second half of the night, but pay attention to keep warm.
How can I see as many meteors as possible tonight?
Note that Geminid meteors come from all directions, so you don't need to watch the radiant.
For shooting a gorgeous meteor shower photo, you need a wide-angle lens with a large aperture. Use high ISO and maximum aperture when shooting.
A tripod, spare batteries and a remote control will be essential for stability and continuity.
What's the difference between laser TV and traditional TV in market positioning?
In my understanding, the traditional TV mentioned by the questioner should refer to LCD TV. The differences between laser TV and LCD TV in market positioning are as follows:
First, laser TVs focus on large screen market.
Compared with LCD TVs which are widely used in the market, laser TVs focus on large screens.
At present, the size of mainstream LCD TVs is mostly from 55 inches to 65 inches, while the size of laser TVs is generally above 75 inches, and the largest is more than 100 inches, which fully meets the needs of users for large-screen color TVs.
Laser TVs have been on the rise in terms of shipments and sales globally, accounting for more than 60 percent of all 80-inch-plus TVs sold.
The reason for this success is the excellent eye protection feature of laser TVs.
The light from the laser TV doesn't shine directly into eyes, but scatters on the surface of the screen. Compared with LCD TV, it's closer to natural imaging process and cause less irritation to eyes.
The expert group from CEITV赛西实验室 and Beijing Union Medical College Hospital conducted a series of experiments on 30 volunteers to compare the health risks of laser TV and LCD TV.
Data confirm that laser TVs do offer a strong eye protection benefit and in some cases an improved benefit.
With the increasing attention to eyesight health, laser TV is not only attracting more and more users by its eye protection advantage, but also opening another breakthrough point in color TV market.
Second, laser TVs are more focused on the high-end market.
In contrast to the continuous decline in LCD TV prices, most of the current laser TVs on the market are priced at over 10,000 yuan. The prices are climbing with the size and light source upgrade.
Why do laser TVs cost so much?
That makes sense to me.
With ongoing improvements in light sources and technology, laser TVs have several advantages over LCDs and projectors.
With ultra-short throw projection technology, laser TV has a shorter projection distance than traditional projection devices. It can achieve a 100-inch screen experience in a short distance. It requires little space and the main unit is small.
In terms of brightness, big-name laser TVs can reach above 2000 lumens.
In addition, it generates less heat and causes less wear and tear on the apparatus, so that the TV can last longer.
In addition, many high-end laser TV models are equipped with a variety of cutting-edge technologies such as true 4K ultra-high definition, artificial intelligence system and bionic screen, which can bring users a more shocking audio-visual experience.
It's not about fake demand, but the result of demand segmentation. In terms of picture quality and input-output ratio, laser TV is not the choice for audio-visual players. If you want to have a big screen and good viewing environment, you can try it. Everything has its advantages and disadvantages. Just make a judgment after weighing both sides. I'm afraid of believing one-sided words.
In short, ultra-wide near focus projector-laser TVs- have to use expensive ultra wide lenses and mirrors to get close to the screen, which is not an optimum optical design.
The cost of using micro-structured Fresnel screens to block out some ambient light is prohibitive. 80" will get you a 65" LCD.
Another thing, I really hate when projection manufacturers use the argument that diffused light is good for eyes. Please, light from a screen that can be seen by eyes is direct light, if it was diffused to the ceiling, eyes would not see it, but if you really want to argue, LCD is also diffused “direct”, when you turn on the TV, the ceiling is also lit up right?
And, a screen that does not diffuse light can't form an image.
What's really uncomfortable is when the hot spot effect of a high gain screen is ignored and reflected into eyes from a certain angle.
